<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Fiji </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabuka Demands `Complete Honesty', Convenes Cabinet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203101594 Hong Kong AFP in English 0853 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0203101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Suva, March 2 (AFP) -- Fiji's newly re-elected 
Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka demanded complete honesty from 
his streamlined cabinet of 12 ministers at their first meeting 
here Wednesday. [passage omitted] 
  Rabuka also stressed that his ministers must discharge their 
duties impartially and serve the government and the people of 
Fiji to the best of their ability. The prime minister also 
requested the ministers disclose in confidence a full list of 
their holdings of stocks in companies and shares they have 
acquired after taking office. 
  His moves followed reports last year that Rabuka's wife and 
one of his cabinet ministers had shares in a construction 
company which had won a five million Fiji dollar (3.2 million US 
dollar) contract to upgrade Fiji's international airport at 
Nadi, on the western edge of the main island. At the time Rabuka 
denied he had anything to do with the awarding of the contract 
to the company, whose bid was the lowest, and later his wife and 
the cabinet minister sold their shares. 

</TEXT>

