<H3> <TI>   Jean Marie Leye Sworn in as New President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203082994 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 2 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0203082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vanuatu has a new president. Jean Marie Leye was 
sworn in today as the country's third president after two 
previous attempts to elect a national leader failed. South 
Pacific correspondent Erina Reddan reports one opposition group 
crossed the floor to support the government's candidate, paving 
the way for a future coalition between the two groups. 
  [Begin Reddan recording] In the third attempt to elect a 
president, the political deadlock was broken when one opposition 
group, the Vanuaaku Pati [VP], voted with the government to 
achieve the required two-thirds majority. 
  Leader of the VP and of the opposition, Donald Kalpokas, is 
confident that within a few days his party will have formally 
joined the government. The VP's nine seats in Parliament will 
bolster Prime Minister Maxine Carlot Korman's slim majority. 
  President Leye, 61 years old, formerly the vice president of 
the ruling Union of Moderate Parties, was elected with 41 votes. 
Five went to Father John Bani, and nine were spoiled or left 
blank. After being sworn in, the president said today's 
consensus was only the start of greater harmony and unity in 
Vanuatu. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

