<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorial to U.S.: Forget About Compensation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0103133594 Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA in Cambodian 26 
Feb 94 p 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0103133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "The United States Should Forget About </F>
Compensation Claims"] 
  [Excerpts] It was like dry-season lightning when the 
foreign press began reporting that the United States began talks 
with Cambodia on 24 February on compensation claims arising from 
the takeover of Cambodia by the communists in 1975. The claims 
also encompass all private debts. 
  The claims by the United States are correct based on the 
view 
that the new government should inherit all the legacies from old 
governments. Logically, however, the United States' demands 
appear to be totally unreasonable. 
  It is widely known that the Polpotists seized all private 
assets, whether or not they were owned by U.S. or Cambodian 
individuals or any other countries. It is widely agreed that 
the current government cannot be accountable for what the Khmer 
Rouge clique seized. The Khmer Rouge pulled themselves out of 
the UN-organized peace process. They should be asked to pay for 
private property they destroyed. If Washington is determined to 
claim compensation, it would only be diplomatic excess. 
Moreover, it is worth noting that what happened in Saigon and 
what happened in Phnom Penh after 1975 were completely different 
-- the communists who confiscated private assets in Cambodia 
have already been outlawed, a situation completely different 
from that in Vietnam. [passage omitted] 
  The United States should forget about compensation claims 
from Cambodia as it has done with other Third World countries. 
What the Cambodian people want to see from the United States is 
its determination to make a success of the international 
conference on the reconstruction of Cambodia to be held in 
Tokyo, Japan, on 10 and 11 March 1994, according to the wish of 
Cambodia, one of the poorest countries of the world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

