<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura Calls Super 301 Revival Unproductive </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203081094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0757 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203081094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's possible move to revive the Super 301 trade 
retaliation mechanism through an executive order would be 
"unproductive" for Japan-U.S. trade relations, Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura said Wednesday [2 March]. 
  "I cannot help describing such a decision to resuscitate the 
Super 301 as unproductive," the top government spokesman told a 
news conference. 
  Noting Tokyo has decided to voluntarily devise a package of 
possible measures to further open its markets by the end of 
March, Takemura said, "we strongly urge the U.S. Government to 
take sensible action." 
  The chief cabinet secretary made the comments after THE NEW 
YORK TIMES reported Clinton is scrambling to reinstate his legal 
authority to impose early sanctions on Japan. 
  Super 301, passed by the U.S. Congress in 1988, gives the 
President the right to retaliate against countries which the 
United States deems to be engaging in unfair trade practices. 

</TEXT>

