<H3> <TI>   Compromise With U.S. Nears on Cellular Phones </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203105994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1034 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
may reach a compromise soon on opening the Japanese cellular 
phone market, negotiating sources said Wednesday [2 March]. 
  As soon as a compromise is reached, the Posts and 
Telecommunications Ministry will start negotiations with the 
U.S. to avert possible U.S. trade sanctions, the sources said. 
  The U.S. has said it will retaliate against Japan if Japan 
fails to open the cellular phone market to the products of 
Motorola Inc. 
  Japanese cellular phone company Nippon Idou Tsushin Corp. 
(IDO) has indicated readiness to make further concessions on 
Motorola's demand for more purchases of its systems and 
equipment. 
  Motorola has said it will urge the U.S. Government not to 
impose sanctions if it reaches a settlement with IDO, according 
to the sources. 
  IDO in January came up with a plan for installation of more 
Motorola-type cellular phone stations, but that failed to 
satisfy the U.S. 
  Under that plan, 134 such stations were to have been 
established by March 1997. 
  But Motorola asked, among other things, that IDO implement 
the plan two years earlier. 
  IDO and Motorola are continuing negotiations on the plan, 
the 
sources said. 

</TEXT>

