<H3> <TI>   BOJ: U.S. GDP Rise Shows Competitiveness </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203004094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0003 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203004094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- A jump in U.S. economic 
growth in the last three months of 1993 was mainly due to a 
steady recovery in U.S. competitiveness in the world market, a 
Bank of Japan [BOJ] source said late Tuesday [1 March]. 
  The source made the remarks shortly after the U.S. Commerce 
Department announced that gross domestic product (GDP) grew 7.5 
percent in annualized terms in the October-December quarter. 
  "Expansion in exports contributed chiefly to the 
improvements," the source said. 
  Touching on the yen-dollar rate, the BOJ source said, "Forex 
players will now shift their attention to economic conditions of 
both countries -- away from Japan's domestic political 
uncertainty -- with mounting expectations that a gap in their 
economic fundamentals will not shrink further for a while." 

</TEXT>

