<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Urge Slashing U.S. Trade Surplus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203031994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0254 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203031994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Parliamentary vice 
ministers Wednesday [2 March] called for the need to slash 
Japan's huge trade surplus in an effort to seek sound bilateral 
ties with the United States, a government spokesman said. 
  At a meeting of parliamentary vice ministers, Yuriko Koike 
of 
the Management and Coordination Agency said that behind strained 
ties between the two nations is Japan's massive trade surplus, 
Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Hatoyama told a news 
conference. 
  Koike reportedly spoke of the need to take necessary surplus 
cutting measures to put Tokyo-Washington ties back on the right 
track. 
  Japan's global trade surplus soared to some 130 billion 
dollars last year, of which about 60 billion dollars was with 
the U.S. 
  Washington has been increasing pressure on Tokyo to whittle 
down its lopsided trade surplus since the collapse of talks on a 
bilateral trade framework in mid-February. 
  Aogu Matsumae, parliamentary vice minister for the Posts and 
Telecommunications Ministry, echoed Koike's view and also called 
for steps to rectify the trade imbalance with the U.S. as 
quickly as possible, Hatoyama said. 
  Noting relations with the U.S. are the most important 
bilateral ties for Japan, Morio Kimura of the Agricultural, 
Forestry and Fisheries Ministry said Tokyo must strive to 
maintain positive relations. 

</TEXT>

