<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Help Ukraine Dismantle Nuclear Arms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203083094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0812 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Japan and Ukraine signed an 
agreement in Kiev on Wednesday [2 March] to cooperate on 
dismantling nuclear weapons in Ukraine and to set up a committee 
for effectively carrying out the work, the Foreign Ministry said. 
  Japanese Ambassador to Ukraine Shoji Suezawa signed the 
agreement with Ukraine Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko, the 
ministry said. 
  The committee will include representatives of the 
Governments 
of Japan and Ukraine, it said. 
  The accord follows Japan's announcement in April last year 
at 
a ministerial meeting of the Group of Seven (G-7) nations that 
it would extend a grant-in-aid of 100 million dollars for the 
promotion of nuclear weapons destruction in the former Soviet 
Union. 
  Ukraine is one of the four former Soviet republics that 
inherited nuclear weapons when the Soviet Union broke up in 1991. 
  Japan signed a similar accord on cooperation on nuclear 
nonproliferation with Belarus in November. Japan has yet to 
sign an agreement with Kazakhstan. 
  In January, U.S. President Bill Clinton, Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk agreed to 
scrap Ukraine's 176 intercontinental ballistic missiles and 
1,800 warheads. 

</TEXT>

