<H3> <TI>   Thai Official Defends Quality of Exported Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203093394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203093394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kitakyushu, Fukuoka Pref., March 2 KYODO -- A Thai 
commerce official Wednesday [2 March] expressed confidence in 
the quality of rice from Thailand, saying it is strictly 
regulated by Bangkok. 
  Churin Laksanawisit, vice minister of commerce, told 
reporters at a Thai products fair here that there are a number 
of domestic quality inspections of rice before it is exported 
and inspected in Japan. 
  The vice minister said Bangkok recognizes the importance of 
value and quality. 
  Japan recently began importing rice on an emergency basis to 
cover shortfalls caused by harvest shortages last year due to an 
unusually cool summer. 
  The rice imports have been met with opposition by Japanese 
farmers and consumer groups, along with reports that some of the 
rice coming into Japan has been discolored by mold. 
  As for the flavor of Thai rice, Laksanawisit began by noting 
that the method of preparing the rice in Japan and Thailand is 
different but added that if Japanese consumers get used to the 
way of cooking Thai rice they would find it delicious. 

</TEXT>

