<H3> <TI>   City Banks To Set Up Brokerage Subsidiaries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802235094 Tokyo KYODO in English 2306 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802235094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 1 KYODO -- The Finance Ministry is to 
give permits to nine major commercial banks including Dai-Ichi 
Kangyo Bank to set up brokerage subsidiaries as early as this 
week, ministry officials said Tuesday [1 March]. 
  The so-called city banks are expected to begin brokering 
businesses such as underwriting corporate bonds this summer, the 
officials said. 
  The move will accelerate reforms of the financial system, 
calling for the breaking down of a "fire wall" separating 
banking and brokerage businesses, a ministry official said. 
  Under the reforms, subsidiaries for brokering businesses 
were 
launched last year by the Industrial Bank of Japan, the 
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, Norinchukin Bank and two trust 
banks. 
  The other eight city banks to be given permits are Sakura, 
Fuji, Sumitomo, Mitsubishi, Tokai, Sanwa, Asahi and Hokkaido 
Takushoku Banks. 

</TEXT>

