<H3> <TI>   Council Recommends Raising Pension Age to 65 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103144794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1438 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 1 KYODO -- A government advisory panel 
on Tuesday [1 March] recommended raising the age at which 
retired corporate employees can draw state-managed retirement 
pensions to 65 from the current 60 in an effort to cope with the 
rapid aging of society, officials said. 
  The National Pension Council made the recommendations in a 
report to Health and Welfare Minister Keigo Ouchi, the officials 
said. 
  The council suggested that the age at which employees 
qualify 
for the welfare pension be gradually raised to 65 from the year 
2001. 
  The ministry plans to submit bills on revision of the 
pension 
system to the current regular Diet session in mid-March for 
approval, they said. 
  One in four people in Japan will be 65 or over by early next 
century. A government survey found that nearly 70 percent of 
people want to work beyond the age of 60. 

</TEXT>

