<H3> <TI>   Curb on Low Public Works Bids Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203101594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0901 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- The chief of a Japanese 
construction industry group Wednesday [2 March] criticized 
another construction industry group's request that member 
companies refrain from "dumping" in their bids for public works 
contracts. 
  Taira Shibata, chairman of the Japan Civil Engineering 
Contractors Association and president of Nishimatsu Construction 
Co., told reporters the proposal to curb bids of less than fair 
value could restrict bid value and contravene the Antimonopoly 
Law. 
  His comments were made in response to the request by Kenji 
Maeda, chairman of the Japan Federation of Construction 
Contractors and president of Maeda Corp., on February 21. 
  Shibata said fair value is difficult to define, since 
contractors sometimes cut their bids through active 
cost-reduction efforts. 
  Low bids also mean more competitive bidding through measures 
to restrict the practice of bid rigging, Shibata said. 

</TEXT>

