<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Smaller Firms See Earnings Hit Bottom </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203095394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0722 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Earnings at small and 
medium-sized firms are poised to hit bottom although labor and 
production facilities remain excessive, Small Business Finance 
Corp. said Wednesday [2 March] in its monthly survey. 
  The government-backed institution said in the February 
survey 
that the diffusion index of profits came to a seasonally 
adjusted minus 26.4 from January's minus 30.7, with the sales 
index improving to minus 14.7 from minus 18.9. 
  Looking three months ahead, the sales index came to minus 
4.4 
from the previous month's minus 6.9, with signs for recovery 
seen particularly in the consumer electronics and public-works 
related construction fields. 
  But the institutions noted "concerns over adverse effects, 
again primarily on subcontractors related to exporters from the 
yen's recent further advance." 
  The index represents the percentage of those answering "an 
increase" minus those saying "a decline." 
  The survey covered 900 smaller firms, with responses 
obtained 
from 662 firms, or 73.6 percent. 
  The product inventory index, or the net saying shortage, 
deteriorated to minus 23.5 from minus 22.1, with stockpiles 
considered excessive on a broad front. 
  The labor shortage index waned to minus 13.9 from minus 
15.5, 
with an excessive labor force continuing in precision equipment, 
steel and auto parts firms although some improvements are seen 
at electric machinery and chemical manufacturers. 

</TEXT>

