<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nikkeiren's Nagano Voices Caution on Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203084194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Takeshi Nagano, one of 
Japan's leading business executives, Wednesday [2 March] 
cautioned against premature optimism over the state of the 
Japanese economy. 
  Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of Employers 
Association [Nikkeiren], told a press conference that the 
"tankan" business survey by the Bank of Japan (BOJ), published 
the previous day, cannot be considered an exact reflection of 
reality. 
  He said the report is "based on figures taken before the 
Japan-U.S. summit meeting" February 11, since when U.S. 
pressure has been mounting on Japan to cut its huge current 
account surplus. 
  "So it is premature to say the economy has bottomed out. 
Last year, signs of recovery were immediately followed by 
worsening of the situation. I cannot be pleased with the report 
without reserve," Nagano said. 
  The tankan report indicated that pessimism among businesses 
has hit bottom, with the BOJ index for business confidence among 
major manufacturers surveyed in February at minus 56, unchanged 
from the previous survey taken in November last year. 
  Nagano also reiterated his proposal for no wage increases in 
the coming fiscal year, starting in April. 
  "Further hikes in wages will encourage hollowing of the 
industry. Japan's wages are already the world's highest in 
nominal terms," he said. 

</TEXT>

