<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Support for Cabinet Drops Below 60 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203005694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0015 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- Popular support for Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's coalition cabinet has fallen below 
the 60 percent mark for the first time since its August 
inauguration, according to opinion polls released Wednesday [2 
March] by two leading dailies. 
  A YOMIURI SHIMBUN survey showed that support fell sharply in 
February to 58 percent, down 14.4 percentage points from the 
previous month. 
  Meanwhile, the disapproval rate increased 11.6 points to 
29.5 
percent. Pollsters surveyed 3,000 eligible voters nationwide 
from February 26 to 27 and got responses from 2,081, or 69 
percent. 
  According to a separate nationwide survey carried out by the 
ASAHI SHIMBUN, support fell to 57 percent from 60 percent 
recorded in a December survey. 
  The paper got responses from 2,318 eligible voters out of a 
sample of 3,000 surveyed from February 27 to 28. 
  It said strong support for Hosokawa personally appeared to 
be 
putting a brake on the slide in his cabinet's popularity, with 
66 percent of respondents expressing confidence in the prime 
minister's leadership abilities. 
  Both dailies noted that the Hosokawa cabinet remains 
significantly more popular than previous Liberal Democratic 
Party administrations. 
  But the YOMIURI said the plunge in support will come as a 
heavy blow to a government that has relied on strong popular 
approval ratings to compensate for its weak base in the Diet. 

</TEXT>

