<H3> <TI>   LDP's Kono Criticizes Turmoil Over Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203081594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0755 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203081594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- The head of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) criticized the 
coalition government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on 
Wednesday [2 March] for its disarray over Hosokawa's plan to 
reshape the cabinet, saying what is imperative now is the 
economic recovery. 
  Yohei Kono, president of the largest opposition party, told 
reporters that the government should commit itself to work on 
bringing the sluggish economy back on track and thus now is not 
the time to reshuffle the cabinet. 
  The LDP has insisted on immediately pushing ahead with 
economic stimulus measures since last year but the Hosokawa 
administration has no idea for shoring up the economy nor 
interest in doing so, Kono said. 
  Sadatoshi Ozato, chairman of the LDP's Diet Affairs 
Committee, also criticized the ruling coalition, telling 
reporters the government has lost its function due to a discord 
between Hosokawa, and his spokesman and Chief of Staff Masayoshi 
Takemura. 
  Ozato urged Hosokawa to bring an immediate end to the 
political turmoil, saying the Diet cannot set up the timetable 
for deliberations of the 73.08 trillion yen budget for fiscal 
1994, which the cabinet will submit to the Diet on Friday. 
  Ruling coalition parties have remained divided over 
Hosokawa's scheme to make changes to his nearly seven-month-old 
cabinet, expected for Thursday. 
  The primary target of the reshuffle is apparently to 
Tamekura, the chief cabinet secretary, who has been reportedly 
at odds with Hosokawa since late December. 

</TEXT>

