<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plans To Buy U.S.-Made Auto Parts Studied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802123294 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2802123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An auto industry source says the Japan Automobile 
Manufacturers Association, headed by Yutaka Kume, has firmed up 
plans to propose to the U.S. automobile industry that a venue be 
agreed at which both automakers from both countries can discuss 
Japanese purchases of American-made auto parts and moves to 
increase sales of American-built cars in Japan. Both issues 
have become the focus of a Japan-U.S. trade row in economic 
framework talks. 
  Toyota Motor Corporation and Nissan Motor Company have begun 
to study plans to purchase American-made auto parts. 
  The Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association and major 
automakers plan to finalize details of plans to purchase 
American-made auto parts in mid-March, at the earliest, in line 
with government plans to open the Japanese market. 
  Strained Japan-U.S. economic relations following the 
breakdown of economic framework talks over the issue of 
numerical targets have prompted the automobile industry, which 
has insisted that Japanese purchases of American-made auto parts 
are not the province of government negotiation, to judge that 
the industry now needs to announce measures to resolve the issue. 

</TEXT>

