<H3> <TI>   Government To Resume Humanitarian Aid to Burma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702143394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Feb 
94 Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2702143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government will resume official development 
assistance (ODA) to Burma where there currently are moves toward 
democratization. This will be the first ODA given to the 
country since 1988. The Japanese Government recently exchanged 
correspondence with the Burmese Government. As a first step, 
Japan will provide the country with approximately 15 million yen 
in March in the form of financial grant. Financial cooperation 
will center on humanitarian aid such as medical equipment via 
nongovernmental organizations (NGO's). The government has not 
yet decided to start full-scale aid such as yen loans, but will 
make a decision after watching the progress of the country's 
democratization efforts. Japan's action is in contrast to that 
of American and European nations, which are being cautious about 
resuming aid to Burma. 

</TEXT>

