<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Posts Ministry To Support Digital HDTV Plans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103222594 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0103222594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It was learned on 27 February that the Ministry of 
Posts and Telecommunications [MOPT] plans to inaugurate in 
fiscal year 1994 a "digital broadcasting technology development 
office" under the Broadcasting Bureau's Engineering Division. 
In a recent news conference, Broadcasting Bureau Director 
General Akimasa Egawa said that the MOPT would not develop a 
digital high-definition television (HDTV) system to replace an 
analog system for the time being. Nevertheless, with the 
setting up of the digital technology development office, the 
ministry will become fully prepared for developing a digital 
system. 
  During a news conference on 22 February, Egawa said: "Most 
countries in the world are pursuing the research and development 
of digital HDTV systems." He stressed the need for MOPT's 
policy switch and called for replacing NHK's analog multiple 
sub-Nyquist sampling encoding system with a digital system. His 
remarks, however, created a great stir. 
  Because his comments brought protests from NHK and the 
Electronic Industries Association of Japan (EIAJ), which is 
selling analog TV sets, Egawa called another news conference the 
next day and said: "Because of my lack of explanations, I have 
caused a misunderstanding. For the time being, the MOPT will 
continue supporting the NHK system." With this, the confusion 
was unsnarled. 
  However, Egawa also said in the news conference that 
"digital 
technology directed toward the 21st century is necessary," thus 
not denying the development of a digital system in the future. 
  According to the MOPT, the plan to set up the digital 
technology development office was actively promoted by Egawa, 
and the setting up of the office was decided on after a request 
for changing the formation of the MOPT, which the ministry had 
submitted together with a fiscal year 1994 budget request, was 
approved. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

