<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hubbard Remark on Security Law </TI></H3>
<H4>   Foreign Ministry Official Reacts </H4>
<F P=102> SK0203030594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0221 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203030594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean Foreign 
Ministry denied Wednesday that the United States has formally 
raised the issue of Seoul abolishing its National Security Law, 
but was looking into the exact nature of comments made by a U.S. 
official last week. 
  "The issue was never officially raised," said one ministry 
official, reacting to remarks attributed to Tom Hubbard, U.S. 
deputy assistant secretary of State, who said Washington wants 
to see democracy take firm root in South Korea and the National 
Security Law repealed. The remarks drew a sensitive reaction 
because Hubbard is the top U.S. working-level representative at 
nuclear talks with North Korea. South Korea's National Security 
Law prohibits any unauthorized contact with North Korea. 
  "We don't believe that Hubbard's statement reflects the 
formal U.S. position, but we are looking into what the exact 
quotes were," said the ministry official. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

