<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hubbard Remark on Security Law </TI></H3>
<H4>   Party Spokesmen Comment </H4>
<F P=102> SK0203041694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean GMT 0300 2 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0203041694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Concerning the recent public remarks made by 
U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary Hubbard, the U.S. side's 
delegate to U.S.-North Korea New York working-level contact, on 
the abolition of the National Security Law in our country, a 
Foreign Ministry official said this issue was never officially 
raised between the ROK and U.S. Governments. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, Ha Sun-pong, a spokesman of the ruling Democratic 
Liberal Party, today made a statement pertaining to the remarks 
of U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary Hubbard, who suggested the 
abolition of the National Security Law. In the statement, he 
said that logically his remarks are not appropriate, and if the 
report on his remarks is true, it is regretful. Spokesman Ha 
Sun-pong noted that he will further inquire into the truth of 
the remarks. 
  Pak Chi-won, spokesman of the opposition Democratic Party, 
in 
a commentary pertaining to Deputy Assistant Secretary Hubbard's 
remarks, said he agrees with the remarks in principle. He 
maintained that Hubbard's remarks should be considered from the 
standpoint of the promotion of human rights and not of 
interference in our domestic affairs. 
  Spokesman Pak Chi-won said that he understood that Deputy 
Assistant Secretary Hubbard also conveyed his position to our 
government, and urged the government to expedite reviewing 
whether the Security Law should be revised or abolished. 

</TEXT>

