<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hubbard Remark on Security Law </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ministry To Contact U.S. </H4>
<F P=102> SK0203085094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0828 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The Foreign Ministry is 
ready to contact U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Tom 
Hubbard about his recent remark that the United States wants to 
see South Korea repeal its National Security Law, officials said 
Wednesday. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu told a National Assembly 
Committee that he would look into the matter, adding that the 
Ministry's director-general of the American Affairs Bureau was 
planning to call Hubbard, officials said. 
  During a seminar held Feb. 25 at American University, 
Hubbard 
said South Korea and the United States differ on "how to respond 
on some regional and global issues." 
  "And despite heartwarming success in establishing democracy 
and marked improvement on the human rights front--or perhaps 
because of them--the United States still wishes the Republic of 
Korea would repeal the National Security Law," Hubbard said. 
  The remarks were deemed sensitive because Hubbard is the top 
U.S. representative at working-level talks with North Korea. 
  Ministry officials were busy denying speculation that the 
remarks were somehow related to discussions between North Korea 
and the United States at their recent nuclear negotiations. 
  The U.S. report on global human rights issued last Feb. 1 
also cites South Korea's National Security Law, basically 
anti-communist in nature, for undermining personal freedoms. 
  Ministry officials claim that the U.S. State Department must 
address the issue "off and on" to placate American human rights 
lobbyists, who reportedly receive "quite a few" petitions about 
the South Korean security law. 
  "The matter has never been raised bilaterally by a 
diplomatic 
agency," one ranking official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

