<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Hubbard Remark on Security Law </TI></H3>
<H4>   Foreign Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> SK0203090994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0810 GMT 2 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0203090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, speaking at a 
Foreign Affairs-Unification Committee meeting today, said that 
the remark by Thomas Hubbard, U.S. deputy assistant secretary of 
State for East Asian Affairs, urging the ROK to abolish the 
National Security Law does not represent an authoritative view 
of the U.S. Government, but was merely a presentation of his 
personal opinion. 
  Minister Han Sung-chu said that the government is planning 
to 
make an official inquiry to the U.S. State Department through 
diplomatic channels about the background and intent of Deputy 
Assistant Secretary Hubbard's remark. 
  Minister Han said that although the U.S. side referred to 
the 
National Security Law in connection with the human rights issue 
in the ROK before the civilian government was launched, no such 
reference has been made since the start of the civilian 
government. Moreover, the U.S. State Department's human rights 
report notes drastic improvement in the ROK's human rights 
situation. 

</TEXT>

