<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul To Announce Suspension of `Team Spirit' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203010094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0038 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203010094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
suspend this year's "Team Spirit," the annual South Korean-U.S. 
joint military exercise, as soon as the two Koreas meet on 
exchanging special envoys at 10 AM Thursday (KST), officials 
said. The inter-Korean contact is one of two preconditions for 
the announcement on Team Spirit's suspension. The second is the 
arrival in Pyongyang of International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) inspectors. 
  Last Saturday, Pyongyang agreed with Washington to allow 
unrestricted IAEA access to its seven declared facilities and to 
accept Seoul's proposal to hold working-level talks on an 
exchange of presidential envoys. In return, Washington was to 
suspend this year's Team Spirit and conduct high-level talks 
with North Korea later this month. 
  The South Korean Government was to announce the suspension 
of 
the military exercise Tuesday afternoon on condition that North 
Korea cooperated with the IAEA's nuclear inspections and agreed 
to hold the working-level contact on envoy exchanges Tuesday. 
But since North Korea postponed the contact until Thursday, 
Seoul also delayed announcement of the military maneuvers' 
suspension. 

</TEXT>

