<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Revising Uruguay Round Tariff Schedule </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203123594 Seoul YONHAP in English 1210 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Mar 2 (YONHAP) -- South Korea has begun to 
revise the market opening schedule under the Uruguay Round 
agreement after learning that the United States has 
substantially changed its schedule. 
  "We have found out that the United States has made a 
substantial change in their schedule," an official at the 
Economic Planning Board said on Wednesday. 
  For instance, he said, Washington now decided to lower 
semiconductor tariff by only 0.7 percentage points from the 
existing 3.7 percent to 3 percent whereas it earlier said they 
would completely lift tariff on semiconductor. 
  About 110 items in the categories of electronics and 
non-ferrous metal would be re-examined by the Korean Government 
for possible change before its final schedule would be forwarded 
to the GATT (General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade) Secretariat 
early next week, the official said. 
  During its recent trade talks with Japan, the United States 
declared they would withdraw the planned removal of tariffs in 
the areas of electronics, non-ferrous metal, lumber and 
distilled liquor. 
  The declaration came after Japan said they would lower 
tariff 
on lumber by 5 percentage points from the present 8 percent to 3 
percent instead of lifting tariff on lumber altogether. 
  "Now that the United States has revised its market opening 
schedule, we intend to make a corresponding change," the 
official said. 
  He added that so far 38 countries including the United 
States, Japan and the European Union (EC) have submitted their 
final schedules to the GATT. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

