<H3> <TI>   DPRK Plans Four New Special Economic Zones </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203083294 Seoul MUNHWA ILBO in Korean 1 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul MUNHWA ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yi Pyong-hwan from Tokyo] </F>
  [Text] In addition to the Tumen River and Najin-Sonbong 
economic zones, North Korea has worked out a plan to set up four 
special economic zones--Chongjin, Nampo, Sinuiju, and 
Wonsan--and a free tourist spot at Mt. Kumgang. North Korea is 
currently reviewing the project in detail to attract foreign 
capital, according to a well-informed source in Tokyo. 
  The source said: "North Korea has already started 
consultations with the U.S. State Department on receiving 
capital, technology, and experience necessary for the 
introduction of the market economic system into the economic 
zones by joining the Asian Development Bank and the 
International Monetary Fund." 
  The source also disclosed that North Korea's former Vice 
Premier Kim Tal-hyon (currently a manager of the Sunchon Vinalon 
plant), who was previously removed from North Korea's power 
circle, is in charge of the project and is secretly serving as a 
dialogue channel with the United States. 

</TEXT>

