<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Nuclear Inspection Sites in DPRK Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203033594 Seoul TONG-A ILBO in Korean 2 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203033594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul TONG-A ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by reporter Kim Cha-su: "Inspection of Nuclear </F>
Facilities in North Korea and Types of Inspections"] 
  [Excerpt] The ordinary [tongsang] inspection of nuclear 
facilities in North Korea by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] will begin on a full scale on 2 March. A 
seven-member inspection team arrived in Pyongyang on 1 March 
afternoon. 
  The targets of its inspection are 16 nuclear facilities, 
including an experimental atomic reactor and critical facilities 
[imgye sisol], a nuclear fuel rod manufacturing plant and 
storage facilities, a uranium mine and uranium smelting plant, 
and two atomic power stations. 
  However, North Korea refused an ad hoc ordinary [imsi 
tongsang] inspection by putting forward its specific position in 
which its withdrawal from the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty 
[NPT] is being withheld. As a result, the IAEA team's inspection 
will be conducted in such a manner as to only confirm whether 
the nuclear material is diverted for military purpose. 
  Therefore, during the forthcoming inspections, examination 
of 
the equipment and work log, and confirmation of the status of 
the seals will be conducted in seven major facilities out of 16 
declared facilities, including an experimental atomic reactor, 
critical and semi-critical facilities, a nuclear fuel rod 
manufacturing plant, a nuclear fuel storage facility, a 
5-megawatt atomic reactor, and a radiochemical laboratory. 
  North Korea ratified the Nuclear Safeguards Accord in April 
1992, and following this, it forwarded for the first time a list 
of 16 nuclear facilities to the IAEA on 4 May. North Korea then 
reported to IAEA in 1992 that it extracted 90 grams of 
plutonium. However, the result of the inspection revealed that 
North Korea seemed to have extracted more, possibly several 
kilograms, thus showing a discrepancy. 
  In a bid to inquire into this discrepancy, the IAEA demanded 
a special inspection of two sites in Yongbyon, which have been 
suspected of being nuclear waste storage facilities. However, 
North Korea rejected the demand, and declared its withdrawal 
from the NPT in 1993. Thus, the North Korean nuclear issue 
became an international problem. [passage omitted on types of 
inspections stipulated in international laws] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

