<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Accepts DPRK Plan for Meeting 3 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203031394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0238 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203031394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government sent a telephone message to North Korea Wednesday 
accepting the North Korean counterproposal to hold a 
working-level contact in Panmunjom at 10 a.m. Thursday to 
discuss problems related to the proposed exchanges of special 
envoys. The message was sent in the name of Song Yong-tae, chief 
South Korean delegate to the inter-Korean contact. Thursday's 
meeting is to be held at "Peace House" on the southern side of 
the border at the truce village. It has been four months since 
South and North Korea last held the working-level contact on 
Oct. 25 last year. 
  "We will go to the Peace House at 10 a.m. Thursday, as you 
have proposed, hoping a successful outcome of the working-level 
contact," Song said. "It is regrettable, however, that you have 
placed responsibility on our side for the suspension of the 
contact and failure to make any progress in the meantime," Song 
said. 
  The exchanges of special envoys between Seoul and Pyongyang 
have to be realized as soon as possible because they were agreed 
upon by both sides for the resolution of the nuclear issue and 
other pending inter-Korean problems, Song told North Korea. 
  "It is important for you (North Korea) to make a sincere and 
productive approach to discussions for the exchanges of special 
envoys, and respect and fulfill commitments you made," Song said. 
  After sending the message, Song told reporters that 
Thursday's meeting could make progress if North Korea does not 
offer preconditions and repeat its past demands that South Korea 
suspend "a nuclear war exercise" and stop participating in "an 
international campaign" against North Korea. Song also said that 
he does not detect any signs of North Korea rejecting further 
working-level contact blaming a delay by South Korea on the 
announcement of the suspension of the joint U.S.-South Korean 
military exercise Team Spirit. But Song said whether or not 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspectors who went 
into North Korea on Tuesday have actually began their work has 
not been confirmed. 
  In any event, if the inter-Korean contact is carried out on 
Thursday, South Korea is expected to announce a conditional 
suspension of the Team Spirit exercise while the U.S. Government 
will make its announcement on a third round of the U.S.-North 
Korean high-level talks tentatively slated for March 21 in 
Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

