<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Show `Flexibility' at N-S Contact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203083994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0818 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- South and North Korea are 
to hold their fourth working-level contact after a four-month 
break on Thursday [3 March], and Seoul is expected to show 
flexibility in discussing North Korea's demand, informed sources 
said Wednesday. 
  Earlier Wednesday, Song Yong-tae, chief South Korean 
delegate 
to the inter-Korean working-level contact, sent a telephone 
message to his North Korean counterpart, Pak Yong-su, accepting 
a North Korean counterproposal to hold the meeting Thursday. 
  With the meeting, Seoul plans to announce the suspension of 
the joint U.S.-South Korean military exercise "Team Spirit," on 
condition that an International Atomic Energy Agency team starts 
inspecting North Korean nuclear facilities and a special envoy 
exchange between the Koreas takes place. 
  The South Korean side is also expected to convey President 
Kim Yong-sam's desire to hold a summit with President Kim 
Il-song as soon as possible and Seoul's willingness to send its 
special envoy to Pyongyang first, the sources said. 
  Song will be accompanied by Chang Chae-yong, director 
general 
of the American Affairs Bureau at the Foreign Ministry, and Kim 
Il-mu, a councilor at the prime minister's office, as members of 
the Southern delegation to Thursday's contact, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

