<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Summit To Address Aid to Koreans in Sakhalin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203110694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0804 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The Japanese Government 
is expected to present measures aimed at helping ethnic Koreans 
in Sakhalin return to their motherland permanently when South 
Korean President Kim Yong-sam visits Tokyo for a summit late 
this month. 
  At the upcoming Seoul-Tokyo summit, Japan is expected to 
explain its efforts to settle past issues between the two 
nations, Yu Pyong-u, director-general of the Asian Affairs 
Bureau at the Foreign Ministry, told the National Assembly's 
Foreign Affairs and National Unification Committee Wednesday. 
  He strongly hinted that the matter of arranging repatriation 
of Koreans on the Russian island would top the summit's agenda, 
along with the North Korean nuclear problem. 
  Tokyo mobilized around 150,000 Koreans for forced labor on 
Sakhalin in the 1940s when Korea was under Japanese colonial 
rule. About 42,000 first-generation Koreans and their 
descendants still live on the island, with an estimated 13,000 
saying they want to spend the rest of their lives in Korea. 
  Seoul holds Japan legally responsible for their repatriation 
and insists that it should bear the cost of their return and 
settlement and living expenses. 
  Repatriation of Koreans on Sakhalin could symbolize 
Seoul-Tokyo attempts to finally put their past behind them, and 
the two governments have already made such diplomatic efforts as 
sending a joint study team in January, Yu said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

