<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Deficit of $478 Million Reported for Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203110894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- South Korea posted a 
trade deficit for the second consecutive month in February, 
officials from the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry said 
Wednesday. 
  Exports totaled 6.23 billion U.S. dollars in February, up 
4.8 
percent from the same month last year, while imports hit 6.7 
billion dollars, up 3.3 percent. 
  The figures showed a February trade deficit of 478 million 
dollars and an accumulated trade deficit of 1.91 billion dollars 
for the first two months of this year, up 389 million dollars 
from the same period a year earlier. 
  During the two months, exports rose 9.3 percent from 1993, 
while imports soared 11.2 percent. 
  Even though light industry exports rose 3 percent and 
exports 
to advanced countries increased 5 percent in February, the trade 
deficit widened because imports of capital goods jumped 15 
percent. 
  The yen's strength boosted exports to Japan for most items. 
Exports to the United States and the European Union rose around 
10 percent thanks to brisk sales of heavy and chemical products 
such as electronics, electric goods and automobiles. 
  Meanwhile, imports of general machinery, precision machinery 
and electric/electronics also jumped 25 percent, 35 percent and 
20 percent, respectively, reflecting rising business activity at 
home. 
  Textile imports surged 70 percent and imports of sea 
products 
and daily commodities climbed 20 percent. 
  Ministry officials predicted imports will continue to rise 
because the domestic economy is on the mend. 
  In February, arrivals of Letters of Credit (L/C) reached 
3.71 
billion dollars, off 0.5 percent from the same month in 1993, 
and import licenses came to 5.53 billion dollars, up 17.8 
percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

