<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reinstates Union-Activist Teachers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203072694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0544 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203072694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- Primary and secondary 
school teachers expelled for joining a teachers' trade union 
four years ago returned to their classrooms on Wednesday. 
  The Education Ministry said 1,135 of the 1,330 teachers 
reinstated in their former profession had reported to new 
assignments across the country. 
  Of the rest, 159 will be assigned to schools during the 
current semester and the remaining 36, who are either members of 
city or county education boards or involved in lawsuits, will be 
given jobs when their board tenure expires or when their cases 
are cleared up. 
  Among the 1,419 teachers expelled for union activities, 89 
were not reinstated for refusing to grant government officials 
an interview, for not taking a refresher course or for vowing to 
continue in the union, the Ministry said. 
  In Seoul, 454 of 508 sacked teachers have been reinstated 
and 
reported to some 340 schools in the capital area. 
  But most schools are expected to avoid placing these 
teachers 
in charge of a class for fear of the influence they, as former 
unionists, may have over students. 

</TEXT>

