<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Force Academy Admits First Foreign Cadet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203073294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0539 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203073294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chongju, South Korea, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The South 
Korean Air Force Academy has admitted the first foreign cadet in 
its 46-year history. 
  A 22-year-old Thai, Natachai Jencharoenwatama, stood proudly 
next to Korean cadets on the campus of the Air Force Academy in 
Chongwon, North Chungchong Province, Tuesday as a member of the 
46th class. 
  Natachai, born in Kanchanaburi, was selected as one of 14 
cadets given the privilege of studying abroad while a freshman 
at the Thai Air Force academy in 1992. 
  He arrived in March last year and took a one-year Korean 
language course at the Seoul National University Language 
Institute before moving on to the North Chungchong campus in 
January. 
  He underwent five weeks of basic military training and tried 
to get used to the unfamiliar language and environment. 
  "I like chicken and pork, but I don't know about kimchi 
yet," 
he said in broken Korean. 
  Natachai has four years of regular courses still ahead and 
will most likely get used to kimchi and many other things Korean 
by then. 
  "I'm prepared to learn the advanced studies and skills of 
the 
Korean Air Force to be an excellent Thai hawk," he said. 
  The Korean Air Force Academy said it will continue to open 
its doors to foreigners as well as recruit female cadets from 
next year. 

</TEXT>

