<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   BOJ: Little Impact on Yen Rate From G-7 Talk </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702081294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 27 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2702081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 27 Feb 94 Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Bank of Japan [BOJ] expects there will be little 
impact on the yen rate despite the fact the G-7 meeting ended 
with member nations failing to clearly define cooperative 
efforts toward stabilizing the exchange market, as Japan had 
hoped. A senior official of the BOJ's International Department 
said: "To a certain degree, the market already reflects the 
fact that the exchange rate was not going to be high on the 
agenda at the latest meeting." 
  At a meeting with the Japanese finance minister, the U.S. 
treasury secretary requested in strong terms that Japan try to 
cut its current account surplus. Some market officials, 
therefore, predict a yen rise in the exchange market early next 
week. However, the BOJ is doubtful, saying, "there does not now 
seem to be an automatic appreciation in the yen when the United 
States takes a hard-line attitude." 

</TEXT>

