<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Laney Cited on Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203080994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0752 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203080994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- U.S. Ambassador to South 
Korea James Laney said Wednesday that Washington will announce a 
four-point agreement with Pyongyang at their working-level 
contact at 11 P.M. Thursday [1400 GMT] (9 A.M. Washington time). 
  The agreement includes the date for a third round of 
high-level talks between the United States and North Korea, 
tentatively slated for March 21 in Geneva. 
  Laney made the disclosure during a meeting with Deputy Prime 
Minister and head of the National Unification Board [NUB] Yi 
Yong-tok. Laney briefed Yi on the process and the content of 
the U.S.-North Korean agreement, according to NUB spokesman Kim 
Hyong-ki. 
  At the meeting, Yi again stressed the South Korean 
Government's position that Seoul and Pyongyang must exchange 
special envoys before the United States and North Korea can hold 
a third round of negotiations. 
  Yi and Laney shared the opinion that Washington and Seoul 
need to consult closely on the issue, the spokesman said. 
  If South and North Korea failed to exchange special envoys 
before March 21, Yi and Laney agreed that North Korea would be 
in a difficult position, Kim added. 

</TEXT>

