<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to UK Press Allegations Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mahathir: No Reversal of Ban </H4>
<F P=102> BK0303091094 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0303091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said he and his cabinet will 
not do anything, including reversing the decision to ban British 
firms from new government contracts, until the British press 
learns to speak the truth. He said it is very difficult for the 
British press to report the truth. 
  He said Malaysia is not asking British Premier John Major to 
apologize or anyone else to do anything to solve the existing 
relations between the two countries. However, the prime 
minister said this is the time for the British press to do the 
right thing. 
  He was replying to questions posed by newsmen after 
attending 
the breaking of fast with the orphaned and handicapped children 
in Kuala Lumpur. Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said that the decision 
made in the cabinet meeting last Friday has nothing to do with 
the British Government, people, and its businessmen. 
  When asked about Major's statement that Malaysia is 
shortsighted and unjustified in banning British firms from new 
government contracts, Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said he will find 
out whether Major's statement was true or just misreported by 
the British press. 

</TEXT>

