<H3> <TI>   General Says KRAF Still Controls Anlung Veng </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203144394 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0203144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On the morning of 2 March, Brigadier General [name 
indistinct] informed reporters that the Anlung Veng area 
bordering Thailand in northern Cambodia -- which government 
forces captured from the Khmer Rouge on [words indistinct] -- 
was still under the control of government troops. This was a 
clarification of news reports that the Anlung Veng area had been 
retaken by the Khmer Rouge. 
  Brig. Gen. [name indistinct] pointed out that in an effort 
to 
expand their territory, Khmer Royal Armed Forces [KRAF] troops 
were currently clearing mines laid around the area by the Khmer 
Rouge. The Khmer Rouge regrouped its troops in a bid to harass 
[words indistinct], where they cut down logs to sell to Thai 
merchants when they still controlled the area. 
  The general said: Our helicopters [words indistinct] to 
bring supplies to KRAF troops in the Anlung Veng area and help 
to defend the area as well. 
  It is worth recalling that Anlung Veng is the Khmer Rouge's 
major stronghold, built in 1979. 

</TEXT>

