<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Hails Thai Action Against Vang Pao </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0303121994 Vientiane KPL in English 0938 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0303121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane KPL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vientiane, March 3 (KPL) -- Brigadier General 
Douangchai Phichit, secretary of the Lao-Thai Border Security 
and Order Commission, February 28, informed KPL correspondent 
that the news that Thai authority is charging and trying to 
apprehend former army generals of the old Vientiane regime -- 
Vang Pao and Thonglit Chokbengboun -- was welcomed in Laos, 
adding that this was a good omen for the increasing relations 
between the two neighbours. 
  The two men were charged and sentenced as enemies of the 
nation and sentenced in absentia by the present regime following 
the establishment of the Lao PDR [People's Democratic Republic] 
in 1975. The men and their followers were recently charged by 
the Thai authority for generating threat to security in Thailand 
by destabilising security and order along the Lao-Thai border 
with an intent to overthrow the regime of the Lao PDR, thus 
jeopardising the relations of good neighbours between Laos and 
Thailand, particularly threatening those living along the border. 
  Brigadier General Douangchai Phichit said that the bilateral 
relations lately have seen marked progress, particularly since 
the first through third meetings of the Joint Cooperation 
Committee for Border Security and Order. This has created 
favourable conditions for making the two countries's border a 
border of peace and friendship. He pointed out that joint border 
committees have been created in several places and memoranda of 
understanding have been signed. One of the tasks of these 
committees is to weed out bad elements that wish to create 
trouble and destabilise the situation. 
  He concluded by hoping that the Thai authority will take 
appropriate measures to deal not only with Vang Pao and Thonglit 
Chokbengboun but others whose intention is to disturb peace and 
security along the Lao-Thai border. 

</TEXT>

