<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Super 301 Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Asked To `Act Sensibly' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0303072494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0711 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303072494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- A senior Japanese trade 
official said Thursday a revival by U.S. President Bill Clinton 
of the so-called "Super 301" provision threatens to shrink world 
trade and urged the U.S. Administration to "act sensibly." 
  Hideaki Kumano, vice minister of international trade and 
industry, speaking at a regular press conference, made the 
warning following news reports that Clinton is ready to 
reinstate the controversial trade law, which would give him 
broad authority to impose retaliatory sanctions against Japan 
over trade disputes. 
  "Such a unilateral approach to solving trade disputes will 
result in a shrinkage of world trade. From the viewpoint of 
GATT rules, a revival would be problematic," Kumano said. 
  U.S. dailies, including THE NEW YORK TIMES, reported 
Wednesday that Clinton has decided to reinstate the "Super 301" 
provision of the 1988 trade law by executive order. 
  "Japan is cautiously watching the U.S. move. The U.S. should 
act sensibly," Kumano said. 

</TEXT>

