<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Super 301 Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Keidanren Head Opposes Super 301 </H4>
<F P=102> OW0303091394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0854 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nagoya, March 3 KYODO -- A Japanese business leader 
said Thursday [3 March] it will take time for Japan's economy to 
recover while admitting that some positive economic signs like 
housing construction have emerged. 
  Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Federation of Economic 
Organizations (Keidanren), said, "it is hard to tell whether 
Japan's economy is at this stage capable of rapidly recovering. 
We have problems like the yen's surge and asset deflation." 
  Referring to reports that the United States may revive its 
Super 301 trade legislation, Hiraiwa said, "I hope the U.S. 
will not take such punitive measures against Japan." He said 
that instead "Japan needs to carry out practical and concrete 
steps...to stimulate domestic demand, relax various government 
regulations, and open up its markets." 

</TEXT>

