<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Refutes U.S. Claims on Bilateral Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303134194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1318 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan has sent to U.S. 
trade officials letters refuting their claims that past 
bilateral trade agreements have not served to open Japan's 
markets, a Japanese trade official said Thursday. 
  In letters sent to U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
and other U.S. officials, the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry insisted that many pacts have worked well on 
raising imports of U.S. products, the official said. These 
letters point to the fact that Japan's imports of U.S. beef 
nearly doubled in 1992 from 1988 following a bilateral trade 
agreement and that the ratio of foreign products to government 
purchases of computers climbed to 18.9 percent in fiscal 1992 
from 8.8 percent in fiscal 1991. 
  Also cited in these letters are statistics showing an 
increase in sales of imported autos in defiance of a general 
market slump and progress in cooperation between Japanese and 
U.S. firms in boosting the U.S. share in Japan's chip market. 
In bilateral talks on a new trade framework, the United States 
has insisted past trade pacts have not worked well because of a 
lack of objective criteria. 

</TEXT>

