<H3> <TI>   `Source': Christopher To Meet Hosokawa, Hata </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303123994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1225 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher will hold talks separately with Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata on 
March 10, a senior Foreign Ministry source said Thursday [3 
March]. 
  Trade problems between Japan and the United States are 
expected to be high on the agenda for the talks, government 
sources said. 
  Christopher and Undersecretary of Defense Frank Wisner will 
participate the same day in security consultations with Hata and 
Defense Agency Director General Kazuo Aichi, the ministry source 
said. 
  The consultations are expected to take up matters pertaining 
to the bilateral alliance and the issue of North Korea's nuclear 
program. 
  Christopher, who arrives in Japan on March 9 on a 
four-nation 
trip to Asia and Australia, is also expected to attend a meeting 
in Tokyo of the International Committee on Reconstruction of 
Cambodia (ICORC). 
  The secretary of state said in an interview Wednesday that 
he 
expects political and security ties between the U.S. and Japan 
will remain intact despite bilateral trade woes. 
  "Our relationship on the first two aspects is excellent and 
I 
would not expect it to be negatively affected by the economic 
matters we are going to be discussing or economic actions to be 
taken," he said. 

</TEXT>

