<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Toyota Plans To Import $6 Billion in Auto Parts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303112294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1101 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nagoya, March 3 KYODO -- Japan's largest auto 
manufacturer Toyota Motor Corp. will probably announce a 
vountary target of purchasing a six billion dollar U.S.-made 
auto parts in fiscal 1996, industrial sources said Thursday [3 
March]. 
  Other automakers are likely to follow suit in an apparent 
effort to break an impasse in trade talks between Japan and the 
United States, the sources added. 
  Japan's 11 auto makers pledged to buy U.S. auto parts worth 
19 billion dollars in fiscal 1994 as part of efforts to reduce 
Japan's huge trade surplus when then U.S. President Gerge Bush 
visited Tokyo in 1992. 
  Earlier in the day, Toyota Chairman Shoichiro Toyoda showed 
a 
positive stance on setting a voluntary target for imports of 
U.S. auto parts. 
  Toyoda suggested at a news conference that the Japanese side 
could propose the voluntary target on condition that the U.S. 
does not take a retaliatory measure if Japanese automakers fail 
to realize such an objective. 
  Toyoda said the auto manufacturers of Japan and the U.S. are 
on good terms, adding it is better to set a voluntary target 
than to damage the relations between them. 
  The economic relations between Japan and the U.S. have been 
strained since February 11 when Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
and U.S. President Bill Clinton failed to reach agreement on a 
U.S. demand for setting numerical targets to gauge the openness 
of Japanese markets to American products. 
  The bilateral trade negotiations have centered on four 
fields 
-- autos and auto parts, medical equipment, telecommunications 
products and insurance services. 
  On Wednesday, Clinton indicated that he will soon revive the 
super 301 provision of the 1988 omnibus trade act, which would 
allow for retaliatory measures against countries deemed to be 
engaging in unfair trade practices. 
  Toyoda has been named new chairman of the Federation of 
Economic Organizations (Keidanren) to replace Gaishi Hiraiwa, 
chairman of Tokyo Electric Power Co. 

</TEXT>

