<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Plans To Urge PRC To Open Markets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303091194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0850 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan will urge China 
through the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) to cut 
its tariffs and open its markets to foreign products, government 
officials said Thursday [3 March]. 
  The requests will be included in a list of recommendations 
Japan will submit to a GATT working committee to help China join 
GATT at an early stage, as it hopes to, the officials said. The 
committee opens a meeting in Geneva on March 15. 
  China, on receiving such recommendations from GATT member 
nations, is expected to submit a list of proposed tariff cuts to 
GATT by next summer. 
  Under an agreement reached last year at the Uruguay Round of 
global trade talks, Japan is to cut its tariffs by an average 
1.5 percent and the United States and European nations are to 
reduce theirs by 3.0 percent. 
  China's high tariffs have hindered its admission to GATT. 
  The Chinese tariffs are believed to average more than 40 
percent, although China itself puts the average at 22 percent. 
  The Japanese-proposed tariff cuts for China are expected to 
cover hundreds of items, including automobiles, machinery and 
electronics products, the officials said. 
  The World Trade Organization (WTO), which is to replace GATT 
in January 1995, is expected to impose stricter conditions for 
admission than GATT. 
  All GATT members, however, will be allowed to join the WTO. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

