<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Car Exports to PRC Soar Prior to Duty Hikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303092394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0826 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan's exports of 
completed cars to China are increasing dramatically ahead of 
customs duties to be slapped on imports of autos by foreign 
firms, industry sources said Thursday [3 March]. 
  Foreign companies in China "are rushing to buy foreign cars 
before the duty is imposed," an official at Nissan Motor Co. 
said. 
  "But the boom will be short-lived. After the duties are 
slapped on in April, shipments will plunge," he said. 
  In January, the Chinese Government decided to impose a 
uniform 110 percent custom duty on cars to be purchased by both 
domestic and foreign companies. The latter have up to now been 
allowed to import cars duty-free. 
  Under the tax reforms, import licenses issued last year will 
be extended to the end of March. This gave foreign firms 
operating in China a three-month grace period to import 
duty-free cars. 
  Nissan shipped some 2,700 vehicles to China in January, more 
than double the number for December. 
  Mazda Motor Corp.'s exports have doubled since December to 
some 250 vehicles a month, according to the industry sources. 
  The Chinese import boom has helped Japanese automakers 
reduce 
their inventories of completed vehicles by more than two-thirds 
from 20,000 at the worst stage last year, they added. 

</TEXT>

