<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dailies Critical of Hosokawa Governing Method </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303022294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0151 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303022294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Two Japanese dailies on 
Thursday criticized Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's method of 
governing as capricious, following his announcement Wednesday of 
giving up his cabinet reshuffle plan. 
  For two weeks the prime minister had been expected to shake 
up his seven-month-old cabinet, ostensibly to better tackle 
economic reform, but apparently intended to oust Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura. 
  The MAINICHI SHIMBUN blamed the confusion and instability in 
the government on Hosokawa's tendency to do the "unexpected" 
rather than on his tactical errors, including most notably his 
abandoned welfare tax and the current crisis over cabinet reform. 
  It was only natural that Hosokawa gave up the cabinet 
reshuffle plan in the end, the MAINICHI said. 
  The YOMIURI SHIMBUN wondered if the prime minister 
understood 
that his tendency is the cause of the stagnation in government. 
  Hosokawa's impulsiveness in decision-making is also to blame 
for the drop in public support for the government from 72.4 
percent last month to 58 percent most recently, the YOMIURI 
suggested. 
  The YOMIURI reasoned that it is natural for the prime 
minister to want to create an "economic reform administration" 
to deal with the issues of recession, budget and trade frictions 
with the U.S. 
  It added, however, that opposition at the heart of the 
administration has crippled the government just as budget 
deliberations are set to begin in the Diet. 
  The MAINICHI opined that the passing of next year's fiscal 
budget to deal with the current economic sluggishness should 
have taken precedence over plans to reform the cabinet. 
  The MAINICHI concluded that no matter how one might consider 
cabinet reform as an exclusive responsibility of the prime 
minister, Hosokawa should first sound out the intentions of the 
coalition members and make adjustments before carry out 
restructuring. 

</TEXT>

