<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saito: Economy Can Absorb Interest Rate Rises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303100594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0928 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Recent rises of long-term 
interest rates and the yen's value are unlikely to put a drag on 
Japan's economy, Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito said Thursday 
[3 March]. 
  Saito told a regular press conference that the climbs were 
recent developments and did not reflect long-term trends. 
  Concerning the interest rates, Saito said rates were rising 
from a very low point and remain at "sufficiently low levels." 
  He said that "at one time" the yen was said to be on another 
uptrend but those expectations did not come about. 
  Saito said more time is needed to watch interest rate and 
currency market trends. 
  Japanese benchmark 10-year government bond yields jumped 
Monday to 3.94 percent, their highest level since just before 
the Bank of Japan cut its official discount rate to a record low 
1.75 percent a year in September. 
  Banks are moving to raise their long-term prime lending 
rates, which would put upward pressure on housing loan rates. 
  Market players have cited a halt in the decline of business 
confidence signaled by a key survey released Monday, and 
concerns of oversupply in the wake of the government's 
stepped-up bond issuance. 
  The yen also climbed Monday as reports circulated that the 
United States would revive a retaliatory trade law, rekindling 
bilateral trade friction and heightening expectations of U.S. 
backing of a higher yen to curb Japan's huge trade surplus. 
  On the economy, Saito said there had been worries in some 
quarters of further setbacks but they have dissipated. On the 
other hand, he said, there is still no confirmation that the 
economy is bottoming out. 
  It is still too early to judge the economy based on recent 
statistics showing some hope that the worst is over, he said. 
  But he repeated that the effects of last month's 15.25 
trillion yen economic stimulus package have yet to be felt and 
expressed hope that the measures will get the economy on track 
for a strong recovery in the fiscal year starting next month and 
stable growth starting in the following fiscal year. 
  Saito declined comment on reports that President Bill 
Clinton 
will revive the super 301 retaliatory trade provision, saying 
nothing official has been decided. He said Japan's policy 
remains not to draft numerical targets to gauge progress in 
opening markets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

