<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   N-S Talks Resume After Four-Month Break </TI></H3>
<H4>   Outcome of Contact Noted </H4>
<F P=102> SK0303060194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0554 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0303060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Panmunjom, March 3 (YONHAP) -- South and North Korea 
resumed their dialogue for the first time in four months 
Thursday but ended their meeting without reaching any 
substantial agreement on the exchange of special envoys to help 
resolve the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  The two sides, however, agreed to meet again at 10 AM next 
Wednesday at Tongil-gak on the northern side of the 
demilitarized [zone] in the truce village of Panmunjom. 
  The delegates to the fourth working-level inter-Korean 
contact could not even take up the problems related to the 
exchange of special envoys when North Korea demanded that they 
first discuss two new issues. 
  North Korea demanded that South Korea stop trying to deploy 
Patriot anti-missile missile and clarify recent remarks by South 
Korean President Kim Yong-sam. 
  The southern delegation, led by Song Yong-tae, vice minister 
of the National Unification Board, proposed at the meeting a 
13-point agenda for discussions including the implementation of 
the delcaration on the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula 
and the inter-Korean basic accords and a summit between 
President Kim and North Korean President Kim Il-song. 
  Thursday's meeting ended a few hours after the South Korean 
Defense Ministry announced a conditional suspension of the joint 
U.S.-South Korean military exercise "Team Spirit" in Seoul. 
  South Korea and the United States have agreed to suspend the 
military exercise on condition that Pyongyang resume dialogue 
with Seoul for the exchange of special envoys to discuss issues 
including the North Korean nuclear question. 
  "The southern side tabled a revised draft of the proposal 
for 
the exchange of special envoys to help resolve the nuclear issue 
and other measures to improve inter-Korean relations," Song said 
after the meeting. 
  "But we could not make any progress in discussions for the 
exchange of envoys since North Korea raised four conditions," 
Song said. 
  In addition to the two new demands, North Korea wanted South 
Korea to scrap the Team Spirit exercise and stop participating 
in an international campaign against North Korea. The two sides 
are expected to take up the question of exchanging special 
envoys at the next meeting on Wednesday, sources asid. 
  In his opening statement, the South Korean chief delegate 
stressed that South and North Korea will have to exchange their 
special envoys before North Korea could hold a third round of 
high-level talks with the United States, which is tentatively 
slated for March 21 in Vienna. 
  The special envoys have to be exchanged as soon as possible 
so that the two Koreas could solve the nuclear problem as well 
as other pending inter-Korean issues, Song said. 
  Shortly before the meeting started at "Peace House" on the 
southern side of the demilitarized zone, Song met with the 
northern delegates and shook hands with them. He then noted 
that the inter-Korean contact was suspended in October last year 
"when the winter began to set in." 
  "As we are meeting you here again today, we feel like we are 
waking up from a long hibernation," Song told the northern 
delegation led by his counterpart, Pak Yong-su. 
  "I hope that the inter-Korean relations will also wake up 
from a long winter sleep and spring arrives in Panmunjom," Song 
added. 
  The North Korean chief delegate deplored that "we wasted a 
whole season since we met each other last fall when grains were 
ripe for harvest." 
  "Let us try to clear up problems for the exchange of special 
envoys within today," Pak said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

