<H3> <TI>   DLP Comments on U.S. Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0303052294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0433 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0303052294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 3 (YONHAP) -- The ruling Democratic 
Liberal Party on Thursday refuted a U.S. State Department 
statement confirming Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for 
East Asia and the Pacific Tom Hubbard's recent remarks calling 
on Seoul to repeal its National Security Law as the official 
U.S. position. 
  Emerging from a staff meeting presided over by Chairman Kim 
Chong-pil, Party Spokesman Ha Sun-pong issued a statment 
rebuking the U.S. State Department statement. 
  Noting that the National Security Law's abolition has been 
one of North Korea's consistent demands, Ha said the question of 
repealing this law must be dealt with carefully because North 
Korea has not yet guaranteed the transparency of its nuclear 
program and because the North's military threat still exists. 
  Chairman Kim said, "I don't think Deputy Assistant Secretary 
of State Hubbard made such remarks with any knowledge about 
North Korean laws... I can't understand why he raised such a 
sensitive issue at this point of time." 
  Secretary-General Mun Chong-su called Hubbard's remarks "an 
intervention of domestic affairs" and criticized the opposition 
party for its support of the comments. 
  Chief Policy-maker Yi Se-ki supported Mun, saying the 
opposition party should take a stand against such remarks. 

</TEXT>

