<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Announces Suspension of `Team Spirit' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0303020694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0155 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0303020694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 3 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government announced conditional suspension of this year's "Team 
Spirit," the annual joint South Korean-U.S. military exercise, 
on Thursday morning. 
  The Defense Ministry said in the announcement that, in view 
of recent progress on the North Korean nuclear problem, South 
Korea and the United States have agreed on Team Spirit '94's 
conditional suspension. 
  "In view of this progress, the governments of the Republic 
of 
Korea and the United States have decided to suspend Team Spirit 
'94 with the expectation that the IAEA [International Atomic 
Energy Agency] inspection of the North Korean nuclear facilities 
will be successfully concluded and that practical discussion 
toward the resolution of the North Korean nuclear question will 
be undertaken through the exchange of special envoys between 
South and North Korea," the statement said. 
  "If the above steps are not fulfilled," it continued, "the 
governments of the Republic of Korea and the United States will 
reconsider the decision to suspend Team Spirit '94." 
  After the announcement, a ministry spokesman explained some 
of its terms. 
  "It's fundamentally up to the IAEA to judge if the 
inspection 
has been successfully concluded. We think every inspection 
activity of the IAEA inspection team should be carried out 
without any restrictions and the results of the inspection 
should be understandable to the IAEA as well as to the 
international community." 
  Last Saturday, Pyongyang told Washington it would allow 
unrestricted IAEA access to seven declared facilities and accept 
Seoul's proposal to hold working-level talks on exchanging 
presidential envoys. 
  In return, Washington was to suspend this year's Team Spirit 
and conduct high-level talks with North Korea later this month. 
  At the beginning of the announcement, the government judged 
that progress has been made on the nuclear issue. 
  "Recently, progress has been achieved on the North Korean 
nuclear question, as North Korea has agreed to accept the 
inspection activities which were requested by the IAEA of the 
seven declared nuclear facilities. North Korea has also agreed 
to reopen working-level contacts in order to discuss the 
exchange of special envoys between South and North Korea." 
  Meanwhile, Defense Ministry officials explained that the 
government suspended Team Spirit because IAEA inspections of 
North Korean nuclear facilities began on Thursday and 
inter-Korean contact on exchanging special envoys has resumed. 
  The South Korean Government was to announce the suspension 
of 
the military exercise Tuesday afternoon on condition that North 
Korea cooperated with the IAEA nuclear inspections and agreed to 
hold the working-level contact on envoy exchanges Tuesday. 
  But since Pyongyang postponed the contact until Thursday, 
Seoul also delayed announcement of the military maneuvers' 
suspension. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

