<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK-Flagged Vessels Said Allowed Into Chongjin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0303093694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0900 GMT 3 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0303093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] North Korea has been allowing ROK-flagged vessels to 
enter its Chongjin port, which has been designated as a free 
trade port, since August last year, according to a high-ranking 
Western diplomatic source. The source said that since it 
designated Chongjin port as a free trade port, North Korea has 
been allowing ROK-flagged vessels to enter Chongjin port, 
reviewing the feasibility on a case-by-case basis. 
  Accordingly, three large-size cargo ships carrying used 
entered Chongjin port flying ROK flags last August, and the used 
cars were exported to the Yanbian region in China via an 
overland route, the source added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

