<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Plans To Expand Chongjin Port Facilities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203023394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0201 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203023394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 2 (YONHAP) -- North Korea plans to 
drastically expand the cargo-handling capacity at Chongjin port, 
which was earlier selected as a free economic area along with 
the Najin-Sonbong free trade zone, informed sources here said on 
Wednesday. Pyongyang wants to develop Chongjin port on the East 
Sea [Sea of Japan] because of its potential as a link with China 
and Russia by land and sea when the North Korean region near the 
Tuman River opens up to foreign investment. 
  North Korea's committee on promotion of external economic 
cooperation recently distributed pamphlets on the project to 
develop Chongjin port to Western financial institutions and 
investors here, explaining how Pyongyang wants to gradually 
expand the port's capacity to transfer and handle cargo up to 20 
million tons and 10 million tons, respectively, by the early 
2000s. In doing so, North Korea will construct a container 
terminal for 1 million tons of cargo next year and expand the 
present seven quays. It will also dredge a 700,000-square-meter 
area in front of the port and build storage facilities covering 
560,000 square meters. 
  Chongjin port currently sits on a 300,000-square-meter site 
and the total length of its quay is 2,138 meters. It can 
accommodate 105,000 tons of ships, or eight 10,000-ton ships and 
five 1,000-ton ships, at a time and 8 million tons of cargo a 
year. Pyongyang also plans to lay rails linking 
Najin-Sonbong-Chongjin-Hunchun (China)-Khasan (Russia)-Posyet 
(Russia) to improve the transportation system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

