<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Said Planning To Increase Trade Pressure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203030394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0105 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203030394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- The United States is 
waiting to apply trade pressure on South Korea until after the 
North Korean nuclear problem is resolved, according to reports 
by American consulting firms commissioned by the Korea Foreign 
Trade Association (KFTA) Wednesday. The U.S. Government 
currently places top priority on resolving the North Korean 
nuclear question and is therefore refraining from bringing up 
trade issues with Seoul, the reports said. Labeling 10 major 
developing economies, including South Korea, as "Big Emerging 
Markets (BEMs), Washington decided earlier to focus on widening 
its access to these markets as this year's top trade policy. 
But it has reportedly made South Korea an exception until the 
North Korean problem is settled. 
  The United States will instead concentrate on improving 
trade 
conditions in Japan and all other BEMs excepting Korea. It has 
chosen Indonesia to test the policy first and is limiting trade 
pressure against Korea to merely "telling what it wants" through 
the bilateral Dialogue for Economic Cooperation (DEC) channel, 
the reports said. But Washington is expected to turn up the heat 
on Seoul sometime before June as tensions from the nuclear 
problem slowly ease and the Uruguay Round [UR] act is likely to 
pass congress around then, they said. 
  Its trade demands will aim mainly at Korea's financial 
services market and policy on corporate competitiveness, which 
were excluded from the UR negotiations, and Washington has 
alreadly begun dropping hints through the dec channel to soften 
the blow, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

