<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Simplifies Foreign Investment Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203033694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0043 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203033694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- Beginning Wednesday, 
foreigners applying for investment in South Korea will be told 
within three hours whether their application forms and other 
supporting documents have been prepared properly and within 15 
days, instead of the previous 30, whether their applications 
have been approved. Moreover, procedures for foreign-invested 
firms to expand into areas not covered by their initial 
investment plans and for foreign investors to sell stocks will 
be greatly simplified. 
  Foreigners may now invest in tourist hotels simply by 
registering their investment plans with the government. 
  These are highlights of the new regulations governing 
foreign 
investment that the Finance Ministry put into effect on 
Wednesday under the revised foreign capital inducement law. 
  Under the new rules, the government cannot reject foreign 
investment in areas where such investment could lead to monopoly 
of or encroachment on the domestic market, though it can still 
reject foreign investment in areas sensitive to public order and 
morals, national security and national health and environment. 
  The business of handling foreign investment applications 
will 
be transferred from the Bank of Korea to all domestic foreign 
exchange banks, effective July 1. 
  The new foreign investment rules are expected to increase 
foreign investment in domestic industries, ministry officials 
said. 

</TEXT>

