<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Urges Nation To Form Security Vision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0203072394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0633 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0203072394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 2 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
said Wednesday that Koreans should start forming a vision for a 
unified Korea in the 21st century while striving to maintain 
collective security in the Asia-Pacific region. In an address 
at the commencement ceremony of the Korea Military Academy's 
50th class, Kim said a unified Korea would not be a burden to 
the peace and prosperity of the Asia and Pacific region. 
Rather, it would be a promoter of such ideals, he said. Kim is 
the first civilian president to give a commencement address at 
the military academy in more than three decades. 
  "Responding to the demands of the times, our military has to 
develop into an efficient, scientific, future-oriented and 
internationalized Armed Force," Kim said. 
  "We have to build an Armed Force of quality rather than 
quantity," the president said. The military must undertake 
reform and change not because of demands from the outside, but 
in its own best interests, he said. 
  "As the commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces of this 
country," Kim said, "I will try to do my best not to betray the 
love and trust of our officers and men." 
  "I'll take a deep interest in building up an elite force and 
improving conditions for professional soldiers," Kim said. 
  The president noted that North Korea is now standing at an 
important crossroads and the world community is gravely 
concerned about its actions. 
  "North Korea will have to guarantee transparency of its 
nuclear safeguards and make sincere efforts to solve the nuclear 
problem peacefully," Kim said. 
  Unless South Korea maintains a strong security setup, it 
cannot expect to attain true independence, Kim said. "We have to 
maintain a defense system that can meet any change in security 
and be alert at all times in this transitory period." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

