<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Fiji </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indians Not To Join Regime If No Charter Changes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0303084894 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 3 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0303084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Fiji's opposition leader says Indians will not 
accept the place in the government of Prime Minister Sitiveni 
Rabuka until there are changes to Fiji's constitution. This 
comes after Mr. Rabuka, after being reelected prime minister 
following the recent Fiji elections, said he hoped the 
Government of National Unity could be formed within the next 
five years. [sentence as heard] 
  Opposition Leader Jai Ram Reddy says before that can happen 
there must be a review of Fiji's 1990 constitution, which he 
says discriminates against Indians and ensures they remain in a 
parliamentary minority. Terms of reference have been agreed for 
a constitutional review, which must be completed by 1997. In 
last month elections, Mr. Reddy's National Federation Party won 
20 of the 27 seats set aside for Indians in Fiji's 70-seat 
parliament. Indians make up 45 percent of Fiji's population. 

</TEXT>

