<H3> <TI>   Rebel Group Still Has `Significant Firepower' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0303062094 Quezon City MALAYA in English 26 Feb 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK0303062094 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City MALAYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Joy Gruta] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Rebolusyonaryong Alyansang Makabayan 
[Revolutionary Nationalist Alliance -- RAM] is far from being a 
weak and spent force as government alleges, said RAM leader 
Gregorio Honasan, who added the RAM still possesses "significant 
firepower," including light anti-tank weapons and other 
high-powered firearms. 
  Honasan said the government does not know the real strength 
and manpower of the movement. "No matter how the information 
machinery and the AFP [Armed Forces of the Philippines] tries to 
dig on us, they still don't know who we are, how many we are, 
and where we are." [passage omitted] Honasan said the RAM will 
surrender its firearms only when the ongoing peace talks end in 
a "comprehensive political settlement." He said RAM leaders have 
given the peace talks another year before declaring them a 
failure. 

</TEXT>

