<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Singaporean Prime Minister Visit, Talks Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets With Vo Van Kiet </H4>
<F P=102> BK0303053294 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
2300 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0303053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet held talks with Prime 
Minister Goh Chok Tong on the afternoon of 2 March. Attending 
the talks on the Vietnamese side were Nguyen Manh Cam, minister 
of foreign affairs; Dau Ngoc Xuan, chairman of the State 
Committee for Cooperation and Investment; Le Van Triet, minister 
of commerce; Ho Te, minister of finance; Vu Quoc Chan, assistant 
to the prime minister; Doan Manh Giao, deputy chairman of the 
Government Office; Vo Hong Phuc, deputy chairman of the State 
Planning Committee; and leading officials of the Ministries of 
Justice, Transportation and Communications, Education and 
Training, and Building and the Tourist and Post and Telegraph 
General Departments. Vietnamese Ambassador to Singapore Nguyen 
Manh Hung also attended the talks. 
  On the Singaporean side were Shunmugan Jayakumar, minister 
of 
foreign affairs; Chen Tong Yeo, minister of trade and industry; 
Teo Chee Hean, minister in charge of finance and communications; 
Toh Hok Ghim, Singaporean ambassador to Vietnam; and many other 
high-ranking Singaporean officials. 
  During the talks, Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet warmly welcomed 
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, his wife, and other distinguished 
Singaporean guests on their first official friendship visit to 
our country, regarding this visit not only as an event of very 
great important significance for the good frienship and 
comprehensive cooperation between the two countries but also as 
an important contribution to the trend of cooperation in the 
region. 
  Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet informed the Singaporean prime 
minister of the multi-faceted achievements of the Vietnamese 
renovation process. He reiterated the foreign policy of 
independence, sovereignty, and openness in the direction of 
diversification and multilateralization and pointed out that the 
nation's primary interest is to focus on its relations with 
countries in the region. 
  The Singaporean prime minister expressed his pleasure at 
visiting Vietnam for the first time and his profound gratitude 
to Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet, his wife, and the Vietnamese 
people for having accorded his delegation a very solemn and 
friendly welcome. 
  The two sides expressed satisfaction at the fast-breaking 
and 
fine development of friendship and cooperation between the 
countries since the visit to Singapore by Prime Minister Vo Van 
Kiet in October 1991. They unanimously agreed with the need to 
broaden scientific, technological, cultural, and tourist 
cooperation because there still remains very great potential for 
bilateral cooperation. 
  The Vietnamese side highly valued Singapore's policy of 
attaching due importance to efforts to strengthen its ties with 
Vietnam, particularly on the economic, trade, and investment 
fronts. It welcomed Singapore's willingness to share its 
development experiences with Vietnam and its continued efforts 
to participate in infrastructure building in Vietnam. 
  The Singaporean side expressed its readiness to cooperate 
with and assist Vietnam in tourist development, encourage 
Singaporean business people to invest in local industrial 
development in Vietnam, exchange international bidding 
experiences, and help with personnel training. 
  The two sides exchanged views on measures to further promote 
multi-faceted cooperation between the two countries for the sake 
of bilateral development and prosperity and for the entire 
region. They also exchanged views on international and regional 
issues of common concern. 
  The Singaporean side welcomed Vietnamese participation in 
ASEAN, regarding this as a positive contribution to cooperation 
and prosperity in the region. It maintained that through its 
participation in the ASEAN special cooperation committees, 
Vietnam will discover appropriate domains for promoting 
Vietnam-ASEAN cooperation, thereby making preparations for ASEAN 
membership. 
  The talks proceeded in an atmosphere of friendship, 
straightfordwardness, and mutual understanding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

