<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nguyen Thi Binh Visits Guinea, Guinea-Bissau </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203005894 Hanoi VNA in English 1507 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0203005894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi VNA March 2 -- Vice President Nguyen Thi Binh 
paid a four-day official visit to the Republic of Guinea as 
guest of President Lansana Conte. 
  The vice president was accompanied by Minister of Public 
Health Nguyen Trong Nhan, Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs 
Nguyen Dy Nien, Deputy Minister of Trade Mai Van Dau, and Deputy 
Minister of Agriculture and Food Industry Nguyen Thien Luan. 
  While there, Vice President Nguyen Thi Binh held talks with 
President Conte and had working sessions with some ministers of 
the Council of Ministers. 
  Present at the talks on Guinea's side were minister of state 
for foreign affairs and international cooperation, minister of 
public health and social affairs, minister of state for national 
education, minister of trade, transport and tourism, minister of 
youth, arts and sports, and other senior officials. 
  Vice President Nguyen Thi Binh and President Lansana Conte 
exchanged views on the international and regional issues of 
common concern. The two sides were pleased at the traditional 
friendship and cooperation between Vietnam and Guinea. They 
reaffirmed their determination to develop and multilateralize 
these relations in [words indistinct] of the two peoples. 
  Mrs Binh highly appreciated the achievements recorded by the 
people of Guinea in the renovation process under the leadership 
of President Conte. 
  President Conte hailed great efforts made by the Vietnamese 
Government aimed at improving the people's daily life and 
building Vietnam into a peaceful, independent and prosperous 
country. 
  On the world situation, the two sides supported efforts by 
the international community aimed at settling all conflicts by 
means of peace. They laid stress on the importance of the 
struggle for a new world economic order and the great role of 
the Non-Aligned Movement and the `Group 77' in this struggle. 
They also agreed to promote and strengthen south-south 
cooperation. 
  Vice President Binh conveyed President Le Duc Anh's 
invitation to President Conte to visit Vietnam. The Guinean 
president accepted the invitation with pleasure. 
  At the end of the visit, the two sides signed an agreement 
on 
economic, cultural, scientific-technological and commercial 
cooperation, and issued a joint communique. Vice President 
Nguyen Thi Binh left Guinea yesterday for Guinea-Bissau, the 
fourth leg of her Africa tour. 

</TEXT>

