<H3> <TI>   KCNA Reports on Hubbard's Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0303044994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0430 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0303044994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Official Stand for Abrogation of `NSL' in South </F>
Korea" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 3 (KCNA) -- Hubbard, U.S. deputy 
assistant secretary of state, speaking at a seminar sponsored by 
American University on February 25, demanded the abrogation of 
the "National Security Law" (NSL) in South Korea, the 
Seoul-based "CBS" reported. 
  On March 1, a spokesman for the U.S. State Department 
confirmed that the remark of Hubbard, a senior U.S. Government 
official, publicly demanding the repeal of the "NSL" reflects 
the official position of the United States. 
  The South Korean authorities and the "Democratic Liberal 
Party" side now are much upset by it, calling it an 
"interference in their internal affairs". 
  Meanwhile, a spokesman for the opposition Democratic Party 
of 
South Korea in a commentary strongly demanded the authorities 
repeal the "NSL", saying it is natural in view of universal 
principles that the U.S. side manifested its official stand 
urging the abrogation of the "NSL". 

</TEXT>

