<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Super 301 Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Officials Urge `Cautious' Action </H4>
<F P=102> OW0303034794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0334 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303034794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa urged the United States on Thursday to be cautious in 
reviving the Super 301 trade retaliation mechanism as a means of 
bringing pressure on Japan to further open its markets to 
foreign competition. 
  "I strongly hope the U.S. Government will take sensible 
action based on a sensible judgment," the premier said at a 
session of the House of Councillors special panel on political 
reform. He made the comment in reply to a question by Hidehisa 
Otsuji of the main opposition Liberal Democratic Party. 
  Hosokawa also said the Japanese Government will be closely 
watching U.S. moves on the matter, in lieu of contemplating 
countermeasures to the potential revival of the Super 301 trade 
law. Super 301, passed by the U.S. Congress in 1988, gives the 
government the right to retaliate against countries which the 
U.S. deems to be engaging in unfair trade practices. 
  U.S. media reports have speculated that the measure might be 
revived for use against Japan following the collapse of 
bilateral trade "framework" talks and as a result of 
Washington's discontent over Tokyo's alleged failure to grant 
sufficient access for U.S. firms to its telecommunications 
market. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura also called on 
the 
U.S. to take a cautious stand over the handling of the lapsed 
Super 301, reiterating that Japan has already decided to 
voluntarily devise a package of measures to further open its 
markets, to be announced by the end of March. "The Japanese 
Government started making efforts to break a stalemate quickly 
and voluntarily," the top government spokesman told a news 
conference, adding that Washington should take such moves by 
Tokyo into account. 
  Meanwhile, a government source on Thursday morning said 
Tokyo 
would file a complaint to the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT) if the U.S. moves to impose sanctions on Japan over 
the spat on access to the Japanese cellular phone market. 
  Saying the revival of Super 301 has already been discounted, 
the source revealed the Japanese Government is considering 
taking the case to the GATT in accordance with international 
rules in order to settle what it perceives as unilateral 
sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5064 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas042_a_94022" </HT>


