<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Suggests Ground Troops Cutback </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303134494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1334 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Thursday [3 March] suggested a cut in the size of 
Japan's ground forces as part of a planned revision of the 
country's basic defense policy that was formulated during the 
Cold War, government officials said. 
  In a meeting with Defense Agency chief Kazuo Aichi, Hosokawa 
reportedly said the revision of the 1976 national defense 
program outline will inevitably focus on the size of the Ground 
Self-Defense Force (GSDF). 
  Hosokawa's remark implies that the strength of the GSDF as 
laid out in the outline could be reduced from 180,000 to less 
than 150,000, the officials said. 
  Hosokawa instructed Aichi to take the lead in revising the 
basic defense policy but do it in such a way as not to cause a 
sense of insecurity among members of the GSDF, the officials 
said. 
  Aichi reported to the prime minister the setting-up of a 
defense agency panel to help review the national defense program 
outline, adopted by the cabinet of Prime Minister Takeo Miki in 
1976. 
  The program calls for the government to maintain Japan-U.S. 
security arrangements to defend Japan against large-scale 
attacks and also to build up Japan's own defense capabilities to 
repel limited-scale invasions. 
  A numerical defense table attached to the outline sets the 
size of the GSDF at 180,000 troops, but the actual number of 
personnel is 152,000, chiefly because of difficulty in 
recruiting volunteers. 
  Apart from the Defense Agency's panel, Hosokawa established 
a 
nine-member consultative council last month to review Japan's 
basic defense policies. 
  The Defense Agency panel will give advice to the prime 
minister's advisory body, officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

