<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   N-S Talks Resume After Four-Month Break </TI></H3>
<H4>   Radio Says No Progress Made </H4>
<F P=102> SK0303044694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0400 GMT 3 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0303044694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to a report from Panmunjom by reporters 
Kim Chong-chin and Kim Chong-ki, North and South Korea started a 
working-level contact at 1000 today at the House of Peace, on 
our side of Panmunjom, to discuss procedures for the exchange of 
special envoys. However, no progress has been made at the 
contact because North Korea again insisted on preconditions for 
the working-level contact. As a result, North and South Korea 
agreed to hold a fourth working-level contact on 9 March at 
Tongilgak, on the North Korean side of Panmunjom. 
  In today's contact, both sides delivered key addresses only. 
They could not enter into discussions on procedural matters. 
  However, the sides reportedly agreed in principle to 
exchange 
special envoys of top leaders at the earliest possible date. 
  In his keynote speech, Song Yong-tae, our side's senior 
delegate, presented a revised letter of agreement on the 
exchange of special envoys. The revised agreement stipulates 
the handling of the nuclear issue by special envoys, the 
implementation of the North-South basic agreement, North-South 
summit talks, and reunification. 
  Our side presented this revised agreement after accepting 
North Korea's proposal that the missions of special envoys be 
specified. Our side had previously insisted that no special 
mission be stipulated. Regarding the method of envoy exchange, 
our side demanded that our side's special envoy be allowed to 
first visit Pyongyang, and said that if the North is willing, 
our side is willing to be flexible. 
  However, contrary to our expectations, the North side again 
put forward in its keynote speech the preconditions for 
working-level contacts which it had previously asserted, 
including the suspension of the international cooperative system 
and so forth. Thus, there was no practical discussion on the 
issue of special envoy exchange. 

</TEXT>

