<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mahathir `Disappointed' over British Inaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203084294 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0203084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir Mohamed says the 
Malaysian Government is disappointed over the British 
Government's silence on the lies spread by the irresponsible 
British media. The British Government also did not act well to 
deny or give a true explanation on the claim by the 
irresponsible media in that country that the Malaysian leaders 
were corrupt. British newspapers frequently attack Datuk Sri 
Dr. Mahathir and other Malaysian leaders of having received 
pay-offs for approving privatized projects to British companies. 
  The prime minister however said that the Malaysian 
Government 
had no quarrel with the British Government and British companies 
when it decided not to offer any new contracts to British 
companies. He made the remarks when breaking the fast with UMNO 
[United Malays National Organization] Youth leaders in Kuala 
Lumpur last night. 
  In another development, the Health Ministry will no longer 
import medicine produced in Britain under the cabinet's 
directive to bar British firms from getting government-funded 
contracts. This was stated by its minister Datuk Lee Kim Sai. 
He said, however, existing contracts with British companies 
would be honored. He said this after presenting a check for 
100,000 ringgit to the nongovernment council on AIDS at its 
office in Kuala Lumpur yesterday. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

