<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Fails To Respond to Overtures for Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403014394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Mar 93 
Morning Edition p 4 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0403014394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The DPRK (North Korea), which has attracted 
attention because of its alleged involvement in nuclear 
development, will start holding South-North working-level 
consultations on 3 March on exchanges of special envoys with the 
ROK. While progress has been made in the promotion of dialogue 
on South-North relations, there is totally no prospect of 
resumption of Japan-DPRK negotiations on normalizing diplomatic 
relations. 
  While welcoming the start of upcoming inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), the Japanese 
Government has indicated its stand that "it will be the best for 
the DPRK too" to rejoin the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty 
(NPT) and to win understanding and cooperation from the 
international community. 
  Since last year, Japan has tried several times in Beijing 
and 
other places to urge the DPRK to resume the preparatory meetings 
on the talks for normalizing bilateral ties. However, there 
have been no responses so far. It is believed that "for the 
DPRK, that attaches the greatest importance to the talks with 
the United States, the issue of normalizing diplomatic relations 
with Japan is of low priority," (according to a Foreign Ministry 
source). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5084 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas043__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-043-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 March 1994 </DATE1>

