<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa Receives Clinton Call </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403013294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0121 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403013294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Friday he received a phone call from U.S. 
President Bill Clinton explaining his decision to reinstate the 
"Super 301" trade provision. 
  The premier declined to elaborate on what was discussed, 
made 
just after midnight Thursday Japan time, but a Japanese 
Government source said both Hosokawa and Clinton agreed to make 
efforts to avoid retaliatory action being taken. [sentence as 
received] 
  The measure gives the U.S. Government power to retaliate 
against trading partners deemed to be engaging in unfair 
practices. The two leaders failed in talks on February 11 to 
agree on a new trade framework to reduce Japan's surplus in 
bilateral trade. 
  Government sources said the Hosokawa government will shortly 
issue a statement to express its regret over the Super 301 
announcement. 

</TEXT>

