<DOCNO> FBIS3-5093 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas043_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-043 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa on Aim of `Super 301' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403140894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1349 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Friday the U.S. decision to reinstate the "Super 
301" trade retaliation provision is aimed at putting pressure on 
Japan. 
  Hosokawa told reporters the United States expects a more 
favorable response from Japan over trade disputes, particularly 
those over cellular phones, insurance and government procurement 
markets. 
  The prime minister said he will take the lead in improving 
ties between Japan and the United States. 
  Hosokawa said he was informed of the U.S. decision in an 
early morning telephone call on Friday by president Bill Clinton. 
  Hosokawa quoted Clinton as saying that the U.S. Congress is 
preparing more rigid trade action and that the reinstatement of 
the Super 301 legislation is considerably more moderate. 
  The premier said, however, it would take a long time for the 
U.S. to actually apply the Super 301 provision. 
  Earlier in the day, Hosokawa said he is not considering any 
immediate steps to counter the fresh U.S. move. "No, none at 
this moment," Hosokawa said. "We agreed to deal with the matter 
coolly," he said. 
  Hosokawa later ordered cabinet ministers to give priority to 
opening the telecommunications market and the distribution 
system in working out economic deregulation to provide foreign 
firms wider access to the Japanese market, government officials 
said. 
  The officials said Hosokawa issued the order at a meeting 
held after a regular cabinet session. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

