<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Minister Hata Expresses Concern </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403032594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0309 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata expressed concern Friday over the U.S. move to revive the 
Super 301 trade weapon, calling it "unilateral." 
  Hata told a news conference that the move is "unilateral 
procedural strengthening" and that he is "concerned about it." 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday announced 
reinstatement of the 1988 trade act's Super 301 portion, which 
allows the president to retaliate against countries deemed to be 
engaging in unfair trade practices. 
  Noting that the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade talks 
completed in December had agreed to prohibit unilateral steps, 
Hata said Japan hopes the United States will act on the trade 
authority carefully. 
  He also indicated Japan will not hesitate to bring its case 
to the world trade body, the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade, if the U.S. uses the weapon against Japan. 
  "Japan wants to resolve the case multilaterally rather than 
bilaterally," he said. 
  Admitting that Japan's unabated current account surplus 
creates frustration in other countries, Hata also emphasized the 
need for Japan to make "meaningful" efforts to cut the surplus. 

</TEXT>

