<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government Issues Statement </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403033294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0325 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403033294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- The following is a statement 
by Chief Cabinet Secretary and government spokesman Masayoshi 
Takemura on the U.S. Decision to reinstate the "Super 301" 
provision: 
  1. The government of the United States has decided to 
reinstate the Super 301 clause through an Executive Order. 
However, unilateral measures not in accordance with the dispute 
settlement rules of the World Trade Organization (WTO) to be 
established as a result of the conclusion of the Uruguay Round 
are explicitly prohibited. At a time when we have essentially 
agreed upon these new international trading rules, the 
Government of Japan cannot keep silent its concerns over this 
move to strengthen procedures enabling the United States to 
initiate unilateral actions against another country in the 
resolution of trade problems. 
  2. While it is necessary to closely watch what sort of 
measures the United States will take based upon the provisions 
of the reinstated Super 301 clause, the Government of Japan, in 
recognition of the responsibility for the development of the 
world economy that Japan and the United States, as the two 
largest economies in the world, bear in striving to maintain 
smooth bilateral economic relations, strongly hopes that the 
Government of the United States will act in a sensible manner, 
and for its part, recognizes the need for a restrained response. 
  3. In this regard, at a recent meeting of cabinet ministers 
concerned with external issues at the ministerial conference for 
economic measures, the Government of Japan reaffirmed its 
intention to advance voluntary measures toward further market 
opening. The Government of Japan is determined to make its 
utmost efforts to strive for smooth operation of our external 
relations, irrespective of the aforementioned moves in the 
United States. 

</TEXT>

