<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Takemura: Government Concerned </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403035294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0339 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Japan on Friday voiced 
concern about U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision to revive 
the "Super 301" trade retaliation mechanism through an executive 
order. 
  "We have to express concern about the U.S. Government move 
to 
build up the strength of its procedures that would clear the way 
for unilateral action in resolving trade disputes with other 
countries," Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a 
news conference. 
  The top government spokesman made the comment after Clinton 
reinstated Thursday the trade measure that gives the U.S. 
Government broad legal authority to impose sanctions unless 
Japan meets U.S. demands on greater access to Japanese markets. 
  Takemura argued that taking unilateral action as a means of 
resolving bilateral trade rows is "implicitly" prohibited under 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade or the 
yet-to-be-created World Trade Organization. 
  Saying both Japan and the United States shoulder heavy 
responsibility for smooth management of the world economy, 
Takemura urged the U.S. Government to "take sensible action." 
  The chief cabinet secretary also reiterated Tokyo is 
determined to do its utmost to further open its markets to 
foreign competition on a voluntary basis. 
  Super 301, passed by the U.S. Congress in 1988, gives the 
President power to retaliate against countries which the U.S. 
deems to be engaging in unfair trade practices. 
  Prime Minister Hosokawa received a phone call from Clinton 
shortly after midnight Thursday Japan time notifying him of the 
decision to resuscitate Super 301, Takemura said. 
  Clinton was quoted as saying the revived provision is not 
intended to target any particular country and that the U.S. and 
Japan can resolve the brewing bilateral trade spat through 
dialogue. 
  Under the provisions spelled out by U.S. Trade 
Representative 
Mickey Kantor on Thursday, the U.S. Government will not identify 
any potential target country until September 30, and will seek 
to negotiate a settlement over a period of 12 to 18 months 
before taking any punitive action. 
  Kantor said, "It should be clearly understood we are not 
designating or identifying any practice of any country today." 
  During the phone call, Hosokawa told Clinton that Tokyo is 
scheduled to devise a package of measures to further open its 
markets by the end of March and said both countries should show 
restraint, Takemura said. 
  Asked if Japan will file a complaint with GATT if the U.S. 
imposes trade sanctions against it, the chief government 
spokesman only reiterated that Tokyo is making voluntary efforts 
to formulate a market-opening package. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5100 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas043_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-043 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Act May Cause Trade `Shrinkage' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403070794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0444 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Japan's Trade Minister 
Hiroshi Kumagai warned Friday that the U.S. decision to 
reinstate the super 301 trade provision may lead to a shrinkage 
of global trade. 
  Kumagai, minister of international trade and industry, told 
a 
press conference after a morning cabinet meeting that the U.S. 
way of trying to resolve trade issues through unilateral 
measures carries the risk of shrinking trade as a whole. 
  "It is worrying that the U.S. strengthened the trade 
retaliation authority at a time when the international community 
is trying to boost free-market rules," he said. 
  Kumagai said the top priority for Japan now is to wrap up 
market- opening measures by the end of March as planned. 
  "I don't think the Japanese market is unfair or exclusive, 
but nevertheless there is a need to create a market with greater 
transparency," he said. 
  Japan needs to act voluntarily "to prevent Japan-U.S. 
relations from lapsing into a vicious cycle," he said. 

</TEXT>

