<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5101 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas043_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-043 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Reinstatement of `Super 301' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Business Community Reacts to Move </H4>
<F P=102> OW0403131194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1227 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Japan's business community 
reacted with a mixture of caution and anger Friday [4 March] to 
the United States' revival of the so-called super 301 clause 
that allows President Bill Clinton to impose sanctions on 
countries deemed to have unfair trade practices. 
  "I deeply regret the reinstatement of this clause that has 
retaliation as a precondition," said Yutaka Kume, chairman of 
the Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association. 
  Japan's auto industry has been under mounting pressure from 
the United States to boost purchases of U.S. Auto parts to help 
reduce Japan's huge trade surplus with the United States. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor announced Thursday 
that Clinton had signed an executive order reviving the super 
301 clause which authorizes him to identify what Washington 
regards as unfair trade practices subject to retaliation. 
  "Unilateral retaliation runs counter to the spirit of the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT)," said an official 
at a major Japanese automaker. 
  "It's wrong to use the method of linking a macroeconomic 
issue like the (U.S. trade) deficit to a microeconomic issue 
(like auto trade)," he said. 
  Some business people said it remains uncertain whether the 
U.S. will actually take sanctions against Japan. 
  "I wonder if it is possible (for the U.S.) to do it because 
U.S. consumers will be the victims of import restrictions on 
autos," said an executive at one major automaker. 
  But some others pointed to the need for Tokyo to take 
measures to rectify the bilateral trade imbalance, saying Japan 
has been slow in taking action on the issue. 
  "The government should go ahead with macroeconomic measures 
to address the trade surplus by boosting domestic demand and 
recycling the surplus," NEC Corp. President Tadahiro Sekimoto 
said. 

</TEXT>

