<DATE1>  4 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry: Current Account Surplus Rises in Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403070394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0642 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403070394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Japan's current account 
surplus rose 30.9 percent in January from a year before, marking 
a second straight increase after a one-month drop, the Finance 
Ministry said Friday. 
  The figure, representing the net balance in the nation's 
trade in goods and services and some unilateral transfers, 
totaled a preliminary 6.83 billion dollars before adjustments 
for seasonal factors, the ministry said. 
  The January figures followed December's year-on-year gain of 
9.3 percent to 12.57 billion dollars. That was a return to 
Japan's swelling black ink with the rest of the world after a 
November decline broke a string of six straight quarterly 
increases from year-earlier levels. 
  Within the current account, the merchandise trade surplus -- 
the difference between exports and imports of merchandise -- 
rose 15.1 percent in January from a year before to 8.26 billion 
dollars, the ministry said. 
  Exports rose 6.9 percent to 25.36 billion dollars, while 
imports rose 3.3 percent to 17.09 billion dollars. 

</TEXT>

