<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Minister Yamahana Keeps Reform Post </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403071394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0618 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403071394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- Sadao Yamahana, state 
minister in charge of political reform, accepted a request by 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Friday to remain in the 
cabinet to finish work on reforming the election system, 
government officials said. 
  Hosokawa asked Yamahana, former head of the Social 
Democratic 
Party (SDP), to proceed with drawing up districts for the 300 
single-seat constituencies for the House of Representatives, the 
officials said. 
  The request was made as the House of Councillors passed into 
law political reform package amendments that will replace the 
current multiseat districts with 300 single-seat constituencies 
and 200 seats allocated according to popular vote in 11 
electoral units. 
  The package, which also revises regulations on political 
donations by corporations, will be enforced after enactment of a 
law delineating the 300 single-seat constituencies, expected 
this fall. 
  Hosokawa also asked Yamahana to study the possibility of 
lowering the age of voter eligibility from 20 to 18. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

